1
00:00:29,080 --> 00:00:32,360
Mirror, mirror,

2
00:00:33,400 --> 00:00:37,320
who is the ugliest
in the police force?

3
00:00:38,200 --> 00:00:38,880
Huh?

4
00:00:39,920 --> 00:00:41,240
Captain Marleau!

5
00:00:41,840 --> 00:00:47,480
CAPTAIN MARLEAU

6
00:01:07,640 --> 00:01:10,320
Don't worry about it!
Make yourself at home!

7
00:01:10,800 --> 00:01:11,760
Ah...

8
00:01:12,720 --> 00:01:14,480
Are you the Satyr of these woods?

9
00:01:14,880 --> 00:01:16,440
I'm the owner.

10
00:01:16,560 --> 00:01:18,080
Some people have no manners!

11
00:01:18,240 --> 00:01:20,280
The public track is over there,

12
00:01:20,600 --> 00:01:23,000
and this is private property.

13
00:01:23,400 --> 00:01:25,520
I love hazelnut-smelling
prohibited tracks.

14
00:01:26,600 --> 00:01:27,320
It's the law.

15
00:01:27,520 --> 00:01:30,880
Is the stupidest law is the best one?
I'm in luck then.

16
00:01:31,040 --> 00:01:32,880
Sorry, I'm in a hurry.

17
00:01:33,040 --> 00:01:34,440
We're off on the right foot!

18
00:01:34,840 --> 00:01:35,520
Not there!

19
00:01:35,720 --> 00:01:38,040
Yes!

20
00:01:38,240 --> 00:01:40,480
Idiot!
You'll see!

21
00:02:07,440 --> 00:02:11,320
THE NIGHT OF THE RED MOON

22
00:02:59,560 --> 00:03:03,200
POLICE

23
00:03:03,360 --> 00:03:04,320
So?

24
00:03:04,880 --> 00:03:06,160
Sorry, it just finished.

25
00:03:06,320 --> 00:03:08,280
The next episode is at 2:00 a.m.

26
00:03:08,760 --> 00:03:12,520
No way! Can't they do reruns?
I hate that!

27
00:03:53,760 --> 00:03:55,880
The red moon is the most beautiful

28
00:03:56,080 --> 00:04:00,040
because it was in the most beautiful
skies that this immortal appeared.

29
00:04:00,360 --> 00:04:02,080
I'm thirsty for blood, mortal.

30
00:04:02,280 --> 00:04:04,520
I'll eat you, Little Red Riding Hood!

31
00:04:05,040 --> 00:04:06,080
Shut up!

32
00:04:07,040 --> 00:04:09,120
It's serious, Léonard.
This isn't a joke.

33
00:04:09,400 --> 00:04:11,000
You can wait in the car, Manon.

34
00:04:11,200 --> 00:04:14,200
-You promised!
-And you promised to shut up!

35
00:04:16,400 --> 00:04:18,000
Go and wait over there.

36
00:04:18,200 --> 00:04:20,240
-What's the worst that can happen?
-Yeah?

37
00:04:20,960 --> 00:04:22,600
Apparently Chalard hired a guard.

38
00:04:22,800 --> 00:04:25,120
Maybe it's just a rumor,
but we don't know.

39
00:04:27,480 --> 00:04:30,520
Come on, Julien. Let's do a selfie.

40
00:04:30,760 --> 00:04:31,920
-A souvenir.
-Come on.

41
00:04:32,400 --> 00:04:33,760
Ready...

42
00:04:33,920 --> 00:04:35,680
Cheese!

43
00:05:39,080 --> 00:05:40,480
I'll come back with you.

44
00:05:40,640 --> 00:05:43,240
Then we separate, as we said. OK?

45
00:05:43,720 --> 00:05:45,320
Does he think he's God's sidekick.

46
00:05:45,520 --> 00:05:48,200
Don't say that, poor mortal.
He is God.

47
00:05:48,640 --> 00:05:50,240
Amen.

48
00:06:10,560 --> 00:06:13,400
NO TO THE GOLF COURSE

49
00:06:14,320 --> 00:06:15,920
Yeah, that's great.

50
00:06:22,520 --> 00:06:23,840
Little rascals!

51
00:06:34,160 --> 00:06:36,240
I'll make you scatter, you sparrows.

52
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:40,320
-Run!
-Léonard!

53
00:06:52,920 --> 00:06:54,600
Léonard!

54
00:07:00,360 --> 00:07:01,840
Julien!

55
00:07:07,680 --> 00:07:09,080
Julien!

56
00:07:29,840 --> 00:07:30,760
Julien!

57
00:07:32,120 --> 00:07:34,000
Julien!

58
00:07:42,040 --> 00:07:42,840
You know, dear,

59
00:07:43,080 --> 00:07:46,480
-I wanted to tell you a secret.
-What secret, Mom?

60
00:07:46,680 --> 00:07:49,480
Alexis isn't who you think.
He's your...

61
00:07:51,040 --> 00:07:53,920
Your what? Your brother?
Your murderer?

62
00:07:54,080 --> 00:07:56,320
Your dad? Damn!

63
00:07:56,880 --> 00:07:58,280
Where's the circuit breaker?

64
00:07:59,120 --> 00:08:00,200
Damn it!

65
00:08:00,720 --> 00:08:03,240
Alain Peras, Entzheim mayor,
we've lost electricity.

66
00:08:03,440 --> 00:08:05,240
Please send a team quickly.

67
00:08:07,240 --> 00:08:08,400
Shine it higher.

68
00:08:09,440 --> 00:08:10,400
What did they say?

69
00:08:10,600 --> 00:08:13,000
Answering machine.
Third time this year.

70
00:08:13,160 --> 00:08:15,360
I'll have to keep the landline
all day.

71
00:08:15,520 --> 00:08:16,920
You can just not pick up.

72
00:08:17,600 --> 00:08:19,760
After all, you came for nothing.

73
00:08:20,160 --> 00:08:21,920
I can't leave people in the dark.

74
00:08:22,480 --> 00:08:24,360
You mean you can't leave people

75
00:08:24,480 --> 00:08:25,960
in the dark before elections?

76
00:08:26,560 --> 00:08:28,680
Are you afraid
they'll vote for Chalard?

77
00:08:28,840 --> 00:08:30,560
You never know with these people.

78
00:08:30,960 --> 00:08:32,240
Hammer, please.

79
00:08:37,280 --> 00:08:38,360
It's not starting.

80
00:08:39,040 --> 00:08:41,280
It just needs a feminine touch.

81
00:08:46,680 --> 00:08:48,760
And Jeanne said:
"Let there be light!"

82
00:08:48,920 --> 00:08:50,280
And there was light.

83
00:09:08,080 --> 00:09:09,120
And sly and cruel,

84
00:09:09,320 --> 00:09:11,840
she let him leave in the dark
and the rain.

85
00:09:12,960 --> 00:09:15,720
He, who hoped to snore by her side
till the morning.

86
00:09:16,320 --> 00:09:18,800
Because she thought that hell
could always wait.

87
00:09:21,200 --> 00:09:22,520
Have you thought about it?

88
00:09:23,240 --> 00:09:24,400
Listen, Alain...

89
00:09:24,960 --> 00:09:27,200
I love you, you love me,
we love each other.

90
00:09:27,360 --> 00:09:29,560
We don't want to lose what we have.

91
00:09:29,720 --> 00:09:31,280
And what if it's important to me?

92
00:09:31,800 --> 00:09:34,280
Why? Huh? Can you explain?

93
00:09:34,400 --> 00:09:35,400
Why now?

94
00:09:35,600 --> 00:09:37,200
We've been together three years.

95
00:09:37,400 --> 00:09:39,720
-What will it change?
-Maybe you don't care, but

96
00:09:39,880 --> 00:09:42,080
getting married means something
to me.

97
00:09:42,240 --> 00:09:43,520
Yes, you're right.

98
00:09:43,680 --> 00:09:45,640
I don't care about marriage. Come on.

99
00:10:06,760 --> 00:10:09,560
Manon? Manon,
what are you doing there?

100
00:10:09,920 --> 00:10:11,120
What's wrong?

101
00:10:11,960 --> 00:10:15,720
We wanted... we wanted to put up
a banner to protest the golf course

102
00:10:16,400 --> 00:10:18,280
-and he's dead.
-Who's dead?

103
00:10:18,880 --> 00:10:20,560
-Chalard?
-No.

104
00:10:21,040 --> 00:10:22,080
Léonard.

105
00:10:22,600 --> 00:10:24,920
Jeanne, Léonard died in my arms.

106
00:10:26,200 --> 00:10:28,640
And someone else,
but I don't know who.

107
00:10:28,800 --> 00:10:30,360
But he's dead, too.

108
00:10:33,240 --> 00:10:34,160
Hi, Jeanne...

109
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:38,560
Think of me from time to time.

110
00:10:45,440 --> 00:10:46,880
Don't worry, it's OK.

111
00:10:47,920 --> 00:10:49,000
It's OK.

112
00:12:01,600 --> 00:12:03,600
-Captain. How are you?
-Hi, Brière.

113
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:07,520
It's cold today.

114
00:12:08,240 --> 00:12:09,400
Hi, Captain.

115
00:12:09,600 --> 00:12:11,280
-Comrades.
-Thank you.

116
00:12:13,240 --> 00:12:15,560
So, where's Oscar?

117
00:12:15,720 --> 00:12:16,800
-With the body.
-Ah...

118
00:12:17,160 --> 00:12:18,840
-Can you get me a coffee?
-Sure.

119
00:12:19,280 --> 00:12:23,000
Oscar! Hi! It's nice to see you!
Give me a kiss!

120
00:12:23,160 --> 00:12:25,720
It's a pleasure, Captain.

121
00:12:25,880 --> 00:12:27,520
You're still uptight.

122
00:12:27,680 --> 00:12:29,160
You won't forgive me.

123
00:12:29,600 --> 00:12:31,400
-So?
-There it is.

124
00:12:33,680 --> 00:12:34,680
Poor thing...

125
00:12:34,840 --> 00:12:37,400
It should be illegal to die so young.
What happened?

126
00:12:38,320 --> 00:12:39,440
He fell.

127
00:12:39,600 --> 00:12:42,120
A fall of about 5.5 meters.

128
00:12:42,720 --> 00:12:44,000
He fell on his head

129
00:12:44,200 --> 00:12:46,320
causing compression
of the spinal cord,

130
00:12:46,520 --> 00:12:48,880
which would have caused quadriplegia.

131
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:50,880
But that's not the cause of death.

132
00:12:51,040 --> 00:12:54,560
He died from a heart attack
after muscle paralysis.

133
00:12:54,720 --> 00:12:56,320
His posture was tense.

134
00:12:56,960 --> 00:12:58,520
Time of death: 2:08 a.m.

135
00:12:59,040 --> 00:13:02,160
-08? That's very precise...
-His watch.

136
00:13:03,200 --> 00:13:05,680
It stopped on impact.

137
00:13:07,240 --> 00:13:08,600
Do we have his papers?

138
00:13:08,800 --> 00:13:11,720
No, he didn't have them.
But the mayor is there.

139
00:13:11,880 --> 00:13:13,720
He should know who it is.

140
00:13:13,920 --> 00:13:17,880
A kid killed at the top of a tree
at 2:00 a.m., disguised as Zorro.

141
00:13:18,080 --> 00:13:21,160
They say we should guide the youth.
It disgusts me.

142
00:13:25,280 --> 00:13:26,480
We're off again...

143
00:13:26,920 --> 00:13:29,280
I saw him a few times
at the Milles Sources cafe.

144
00:13:30,200 --> 00:13:32,560
They're a bit loud,
but they don't hurt anyone.

145
00:13:32,840 --> 00:13:34,120
Excuse me.

146
00:13:34,320 --> 00:13:37,440
When there's a blackout,
I suddenly become God.

147
00:13:38,120 --> 00:13:39,120
Yes, Geneviève?

148
00:13:40,080 --> 00:13:41,880
Get me another one. That's horrible.

149
00:13:42,040 --> 00:13:43,000
Thanks, bye.

150
00:13:43,200 --> 00:13:45,440
All this to sort out...
There's a dead girl.

151
00:13:45,600 --> 00:13:47,040
But I'm not the mayor.

152
00:13:47,280 --> 00:13:51,000
The mayor needs to sort out
the big dramas and the small ones.

153
00:13:51,200 --> 00:13:52,880
-Do you still need me?
-No.

154
00:13:53,080 --> 00:13:56,440
Yes! Because yesterday,
I met the owner of the dump,

155
00:13:56,640 --> 00:13:58,840
and it was like love at first sight.

156
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:00,880
I want to see him again. Who is it?

157
00:14:01,040 --> 00:14:04,040
Michel Chalard.
A businessman from Entzheim.

158
00:14:04,240 --> 00:14:07,480
He worked in Bordeaux
and he inherited this land.

159
00:14:07,920 --> 00:14:10,880
He's doing something big.
A golf course, entertainment.

160
00:14:11,040 --> 00:14:13,440
That's good
for your electoral campaign.

161
00:14:13,640 --> 00:14:15,880
First: jobs,
second: jobs,

162
00:14:16,040 --> 00:14:17,280
and third: jobs!

163
00:14:17,440 --> 00:14:19,320
It's good for him.
He's running against me.

164
00:14:19,720 --> 00:14:22,440
Captain!
Captain!

165
00:14:22,600 --> 00:14:23,680
There's a new body.

166
00:14:23,880 --> 00:14:26,280
This isn't possible.
What is it about here?

167
00:14:57,720 --> 00:15:01,120
1943 Mauser cartridge,

168
00:15:01,280 --> 00:15:02,640
shot recently.

169
00:15:05,440 --> 00:15:06,720
Ah, there you are.

170
00:15:07,240 --> 00:15:10,000
There's no bullet wound.
How did he die?

171
00:15:10,920 --> 00:15:13,400
There are dead people
everywhere here.

172
00:15:14,920 --> 00:15:16,120
Well, what do we have?

173
00:15:16,760 --> 00:15:18,000
At first glance,

174
00:15:18,200 --> 00:15:21,440
the only wound is a blow
to the left side of the face.

175
00:15:21,600 --> 00:15:22,880
Violent but the only one.

176
00:15:23,920 --> 00:15:25,320
You're telling me that

177
00:15:25,520 --> 00:15:27,440
he was struck and died unconscious?

178
00:15:27,600 --> 00:15:29,480
Some bad luck.

179
00:15:29,680 --> 00:15:32,280
His color is black
and his number is zero.

180
00:15:32,480 --> 00:15:36,320
Given the wound, I'd say
the butt of a Mauser 43.

181
00:15:37,160 --> 00:15:39,600
-From where the shell comes.
-The shell...

182
00:15:39,720 --> 00:15:41,720
So, what's his name?

183
00:15:49,320 --> 00:15:51,920
Robert Perdriel, security guard.

184
00:15:52,160 --> 00:15:54,600
He lived alone with his cat.
I know the type.

185
00:15:54,800 --> 00:15:56,760
What was he guarding here

186
00:15:56,920 --> 00:15:58,640
apart from trees and nettles?

187
00:15:58,880 --> 00:16:01,880
This morning, when I arrived,
I saw tire tracks.

188
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:03,440
Like a quick getaway.

189
00:16:03,600 --> 00:16:06,480
-I think there were at least three.
-Why do you say that?

190
00:16:06,640 --> 00:16:08,480
Footsteps near the tree.

191
00:16:09,040 --> 00:16:10,560
And I found this.

192
00:16:10,720 --> 00:16:13,080
A bit of black synthetic tissue,

193
00:16:13,280 --> 00:16:16,720
burned by an iron.

194
00:16:17,320 --> 00:16:20,000
-A piece of Zorro's cape.
-Yeah?

195
00:16:20,360 --> 00:16:23,440
Sometimes, I just want to kiss you.
I don't know what stops me.

196
00:16:23,600 --> 00:16:25,000
Your breath, maybe.

197
00:16:25,960 --> 00:16:28,160
With your permission, I'm off
to my corpses.

198
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:33,280
Captain! Captain, look what I found.

199
00:16:33,480 --> 00:16:35,440
What is it?
Do you smoke joints?

200
00:16:35,640 --> 00:16:38,280
-I found it near the body.
-Which one? There's plenty.

201
00:16:38,440 --> 00:16:39,200
The second one.

202
00:16:39,360 --> 00:16:40,640
-The big one?
-Yeah.

203
00:16:40,800 --> 00:16:42,440
Good work.

204
00:16:42,720 --> 00:16:44,920
-What did you find?
-Something from Zorro.

205
00:16:46,800 --> 00:16:50,200
To the left, there's Entzheim
about ten kilometers away.

206
00:16:50,360 --> 00:16:52,480
On the right is Ms. Dewaere's
animal park,

207
00:16:52,640 --> 00:16:53,560
the mayor's girlfriend.

208
00:16:53,720 --> 00:16:57,000
Is she the type to climb trees
in a Zorro mask?

209
00:16:57,160 --> 00:16:59,720
In some senses, yes, but... no.

210
00:16:59,920 --> 00:17:01,200
-Do you get it?
-No.

211
00:17:01,400 --> 00:17:04,600
I prefer my jokes to be direct.

212
00:17:05,200 --> 00:17:06,440
Look, Captain.

213
00:17:07,640 --> 00:17:10,000
What are you doing?
You're like a dog.

214
00:17:10,160 --> 00:17:11,440
We're lucky.

215
00:17:12,760 --> 00:17:14,160
Barbie bunny!

216
00:17:14,520 --> 00:17:17,040
The things we find in this forest!
Here.

217
00:17:17,200 --> 00:17:20,040
Go and get my car, we'll meet
at Ms. Dewaere's, OK?

218
00:17:20,200 --> 00:17:22,600
-No, I'd prefer to come with you...
-No.

219
00:17:23,120 --> 00:17:26,000
Fusion couples are like fusion jazz,
I hate it.

220
00:17:28,440 --> 00:17:32,320
A bunny killed a hunter...

221
00:17:32,440 --> 00:17:34,920
It was a bunny who

222
00:17:35,080 --> 00:17:37,160
had a rifle.

223
00:17:51,240 --> 00:17:55,000
WOLF VALLEY

224
00:18:03,320 --> 00:18:05,880
Ms. Dewaere's car left at about 3:00

225
00:18:06,040 --> 00:18:08,000
and the dog barked at around 3:30.

226
00:18:08,360 --> 00:18:09,440
I don't know why.

227
00:18:09,560 --> 00:18:11,040
Did you hear a shot?

228
00:18:11,520 --> 00:18:13,040
Yes, maybe. I think I did.

229
00:18:13,200 --> 00:18:16,160
As it was during the blackout,
I thought nothing of it.

230
00:18:16,320 --> 00:18:17,040
Someone fired?

231
00:18:17,800 --> 00:18:20,520
Yeah, it came
from Michel Chalard's wood.

232
00:18:20,720 --> 00:18:23,640
A shot from a 1943 rifle.

233
00:18:23,840 --> 00:18:25,920
-A Mauser.
-A Mauser 43?

234
00:18:26,640 --> 00:18:28,600
That's from the war.

235
00:18:28,760 --> 00:18:29,760
Who has these guns?

236
00:18:29,920 --> 00:18:32,800
-I thought you'd tell me.
-No, sorry,

237
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:35,040
but I would've noticed
a rifle like that.

238
00:18:35,200 --> 00:18:37,600
-OK, thanks.
-No problem.

239
00:18:38,320 --> 00:18:39,960
Ah, Mr. Gabriel,

240
00:18:40,160 --> 00:18:43,800
I want to show you something,
if I can find it in this mess...

241
00:18:44,120 --> 00:18:46,600
A scarf from a Renaud concert.

242
00:18:46,880 --> 00:18:48,240
Do you know who owns this?

243
00:18:48,600 --> 00:18:49,800
No, I don't.

244
00:18:50,240 --> 00:18:51,040
It's not mine.

245
00:18:52,600 --> 00:18:54,200
OK.

246
00:18:54,360 --> 00:18:56,160
It's nice here.

247
00:18:56,320 --> 00:18:58,440
I like Alsace. I come back often.

248
00:18:58,600 --> 00:19:00,160
It's really nice.

249
00:19:00,720 --> 00:19:03,680
Yeah, yeah, yeah...
is there only one entry to the park?

250
00:19:03,880 --> 00:19:05,480
Yes, the main entry.

251
00:19:05,680 --> 00:19:08,040
After, people drive around
like they want.

252
00:19:09,760 --> 00:19:11,440
-I'll let my boss know.
-OK.

253
00:19:11,640 --> 00:19:14,640
-She doesn't like authority.
-She's not the only one.

254
00:19:15,600 --> 00:19:19,760
Yeah. Dangerous liaisons...
They maintain passion, as...

255
00:19:19,880 --> 00:19:21,640
Malkovich or Werther said...

256
00:19:28,520 --> 00:19:30,360
Get up. The police are here.

257
00:19:30,560 --> 00:19:33,160
Hurry up, you're explaining
to them. Get up.

258
00:19:33,360 --> 00:19:36,200
Jeanne, don't make me do it.
The judge can't put me away.

259
00:19:36,360 --> 00:19:37,680
He'll jump on it.

260
00:19:37,920 --> 00:19:40,600
You can't make me.
I've tried hard, Jeanne.

261
00:19:40,800 --> 00:19:42,320
Six years in the clink, Jeanne.

262
00:19:42,480 --> 00:19:44,080
I can't. I'd prefer to die.

263
00:19:45,640 --> 00:19:46,960
You're so annoying.

264
00:19:47,680 --> 00:19:48,920
And I'm an idiot.

265
00:19:49,480 --> 00:19:50,480
Come on.

266
00:19:57,520 --> 00:19:59,480
I'll get you when they've left.

267
00:19:59,920 --> 00:20:02,640
Wait, Jeanne. I can't find my phone.

268
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:04,880
It must be in the room. I'll find it.

269
00:20:05,040 --> 00:20:05,960
Don't move.

270
00:20:13,200 --> 00:20:15,040
It's hot here.

271
00:20:16,800 --> 00:20:18,200
Les Bidochons, I love it.

272
00:20:18,400 --> 00:20:20,320
-Make yourself at home.
-Thank you.

273
00:20:22,400 --> 00:20:24,400
-Is that your son?
-No, not at all.

274
00:20:24,560 --> 00:20:26,160
It's Mr. Louis, the old guard.

275
00:20:26,360 --> 00:20:29,080
Funny you thought he was my son,
we were the same age.

276
00:20:30,200 --> 00:20:31,760
He died more than 15 years ago.

277
00:20:33,640 --> 00:20:35,040
He has no wrinkles.

278
00:20:35,520 --> 00:20:37,880
-Me, on the other hand...
-Yeah.

279
00:20:38,200 --> 00:20:40,520
I took over his lodge and changed
the decor.

280
00:20:41,760 --> 00:20:44,200
I have simple tastes. I'm an old guy.

281
00:20:45,800 --> 00:20:48,040
-Ah... excuse me.
-It's OK.

282
00:20:53,600 --> 00:20:54,480
Hello?

283
00:20:55,200 --> 00:20:55,840
Yeah.

284
00:20:56,560 --> 00:20:57,560
OK, I'll tell him.

285
00:20:57,800 --> 00:20:59,040
-OK
-Poor thing.

286
00:20:59,200 --> 00:20:59,960
Goodbye.

287
00:21:03,040 --> 00:21:05,240
She said you can go to see her.

288
00:21:05,720 --> 00:21:07,480
She seems gruff, but she's nice.

289
00:21:07,880 --> 00:21:08,960
Yeah. I see.

290
00:21:22,640 --> 00:21:24,360
Do you want to live a boring life?

291
00:21:25,040 --> 00:21:25,960
With no fun?

292
00:21:27,200 --> 00:21:28,800
Do you know what adrenaline is?

293
00:21:29,120 --> 00:21:30,080
Risk?

294
00:21:30,640 --> 00:21:32,240
Putting your life on the line?

295
00:21:33,000 --> 00:21:35,480
In ten minutes, max, you have a rush.

296
00:21:35,880 --> 00:21:37,080
Like a fix, but better.

297
00:21:39,640 --> 00:21:41,480
What's wrong? Are you afraid?

298
00:21:42,080 --> 00:21:43,040
Yes, I'm afraid.

299
00:21:43,600 --> 00:21:44,680
I like it.

300
00:21:47,200 --> 00:21:48,200
I'm coming.

301
00:21:55,760 --> 00:21:57,560
Your coffee's horrible!

302
00:21:57,760 --> 00:21:59,520
Horrible coffee, horrible coffee.

303
00:22:00,320 --> 00:22:03,560
Could I have another cup? No?

304
00:22:04,000 --> 00:22:05,960
You're the type to say no.

305
00:22:06,720 --> 00:22:08,680
Do you need something from me?

306
00:22:08,880 --> 00:22:12,080
Yeah, I wanted to know
if you've seen a witness

307
00:22:12,240 --> 00:22:14,480
because apparently
there's one hiding here.

308
00:22:15,920 --> 00:22:16,560
A witness?

309
00:22:16,880 --> 00:22:18,120
Not a Jehovah's witness.

310
00:22:18,320 --> 00:22:19,920
A murder witness. Double murder.

311
00:22:20,760 --> 00:22:22,040
Who was killed?

312
00:22:22,720 --> 00:22:23,760
Did it happen here?

313
00:22:23,960 --> 00:22:26,360
Look! He's coming! How are you honey?

314
00:22:26,520 --> 00:22:28,560
Do you have pigs? I like pigs.

315
00:22:29,240 --> 00:22:30,680
It's not a farm here.

316
00:22:31,280 --> 00:22:34,920
So, around 2:00 this morning,
did you hear a shot?

317
00:22:35,040 --> 00:22:36,080
You weren't asleep?

318
00:22:37,040 --> 00:22:39,120
-During the blackout?
-You had a blackout?

319
00:22:39,320 --> 00:22:42,200
-Yes.
-That's men. When they drink.

320
00:22:42,320 --> 00:22:43,680
No, during the blackout.

321
00:22:44,720 --> 00:22:47,720
No, I just turned on the generator.

322
00:22:48,080 --> 00:22:49,640
No, I would've heard a shot.

323
00:22:51,080 --> 00:22:53,200
Sound travels far here.

324
00:22:53,320 --> 00:22:54,920
I want to show you something...

325
00:22:55,280 --> 00:22:57,640
I don't know where I found it...
There's a bit...

326
00:22:58,320 --> 00:23:01,200
I often travel so I put everything
in my pockets.

327
00:23:01,320 --> 00:23:02,720
There it is.

328
00:23:03,480 --> 00:23:04,640
Are you familiar with this?

329
00:23:05,240 --> 00:23:06,040
It's the weapon?

330
00:23:06,800 --> 00:23:08,840
It could be, it's that ugly.

331
00:23:09,040 --> 00:23:11,840
Whoever has this phone, my God,

332
00:23:12,000 --> 00:23:14,480
if they're more than nine,
I'd put them in prison

333
00:23:15,040 --> 00:23:17,560
-for bad taste.
-Good news. It's not mine.

334
00:23:18,120 --> 00:23:19,240
You can leave me.

335
00:23:19,520 --> 00:23:22,480
-You're good-natured, you know?
-Yes, I know.

336
00:23:22,640 --> 00:23:25,480
Do you know anyone around here
who collects old guns?

337
00:23:25,680 --> 00:23:28,960
I'm talking things
from the Second World War,

338
00:23:29,160 --> 00:23:31,040
Mausers. Are you into that?

339
00:23:31,200 --> 00:23:32,960
No, it's not my thing.

340
00:23:33,600 --> 00:23:37,560
If I may, weapons are worse taste
than pink phones.

341
00:23:37,720 --> 00:23:38,920
Not wrong.

342
00:23:39,400 --> 00:23:40,760
I have candy, too.

343
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:44,960
You want one?

344
00:23:45,320 --> 00:23:46,480
No, thanks.

345
00:23:57,680 --> 00:23:58,720
Oh, shit.

346
00:23:59,320 --> 00:24:01,360
-That's all we needed.
-Who's that?

347
00:24:01,560 --> 00:24:04,240
-Michel Chalard.
-Ah, the owner.

348
00:24:04,880 --> 00:24:05,880
Marleau?

349
00:24:06,080 --> 00:24:09,040
Captain Marleau. Seeing as
we don't have the same salary,

350
00:24:09,200 --> 00:24:11,000
can you at least speak correctly?

351
00:24:11,680 --> 00:24:12,360
How are you?

352
00:24:12,920 --> 00:24:16,760
Alsace is small. For lovers like us.

353
00:24:16,920 --> 00:24:18,080
You know each other?

354
00:24:18,200 --> 00:24:19,800
Not really, we just met.

355
00:24:19,960 --> 00:24:21,200
But it'll last.

356
00:24:21,360 --> 00:24:23,400
We haven't really met each other.

357
00:24:23,760 --> 00:24:26,400
Michel Chalard,
I'm the owner of the property

358
00:24:26,800 --> 00:24:27,800
where the drama was.

359
00:24:28,240 --> 00:24:29,680
Aspiring mayor, too.

360
00:24:30,080 --> 00:24:30,840
Sofa promotion?

361
00:24:32,040 --> 00:24:33,960
I had a guard for surveillance.

362
00:24:34,680 --> 00:24:36,200
That's who they killed.

363
00:24:36,400 --> 00:24:37,800
Why do you say "they"?

364
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:40,840
How do you know there were several?
What do you know?

365
00:24:41,000 --> 00:24:42,040
Did you see them?

366
00:24:42,200 --> 00:24:43,440
There's a band of them.

367
00:24:44,320 --> 00:24:46,000
They tagged my property walls,

368
00:24:46,160 --> 00:24:48,040
defamed me on the internet.

369
00:24:48,240 --> 00:24:50,720
I complained, but nothing happened.

370
00:24:50,920 --> 00:24:54,080
-Do you know their name?
-No.

371
00:24:54,240 --> 00:24:56,040
They're all anonymous.

372
00:24:56,200 --> 00:24:58,400
A big Z as a signature.

373
00:24:58,560 --> 00:25:00,440
And I'm the bad one.

374
00:25:00,640 --> 00:25:03,520
Even though I'm trying
to bring life back to my home.

375
00:25:03,720 --> 00:25:06,040
-He's good, Zorro.
-The Zorros,

376
00:25:06,240 --> 00:25:08,560
maybe they're afraid
of new Robin Hoods?

377
00:25:08,720 --> 00:25:09,920
Bad Robin Hoods

378
00:25:10,080 --> 00:25:13,200
who apparently bring work
from Samsonite and Goodyear.

379
00:25:13,920 --> 00:25:16,640
I think these kids

380
00:25:16,840 --> 00:25:20,400
were walking on the hazelnut track,
got to your clearing,

381
00:25:20,560 --> 00:25:21,760
and what did they see?

382
00:25:21,960 --> 00:25:23,920
A non-declared construction site.

383
00:25:24,080 --> 00:25:25,400
That's not Republican.

384
00:25:25,800 --> 00:25:27,600
Is that the secret you wanted kept?

385
00:25:27,800 --> 00:25:30,320
Yes, it's true, the authorizations
were slow.

386
00:25:30,520 --> 00:25:32,920
I knew I'd have them,
so, I planned for it.

387
00:25:33,120 --> 00:25:37,040
Like all the big men,
Angela Davis, Marie Curie, etc.

388
00:25:37,240 --> 00:25:40,160
I don't know, this clearing's
always attracted psychos.

389
00:25:40,360 --> 00:25:42,320
They came to do their things.

390
00:25:42,520 --> 00:25:44,480
Now, kids come to smoke joints,

391
00:25:44,640 --> 00:25:46,120
so, I got a guard,

392
00:25:46,560 --> 00:25:48,160
Robert Perdriel, a brave man.

393
00:25:48,320 --> 00:25:50,040
Did he smoke or carry joints?

394
00:25:51,200 --> 00:25:53,400
Was he armed? No, I don't think so.

395
00:25:53,560 --> 00:25:54,320
No...

396
00:25:54,880 --> 00:25:57,160
I wanted to show you.
Do you know this phone?

397
00:25:57,320 --> 00:26:00,400
Ah, speaking of phones... excuse me.

398
00:26:04,480 --> 00:26:07,560
Yes... yes, you're going to hurt me?

399
00:26:09,480 --> 00:26:10,960
It will be incredible.

400
00:26:11,400 --> 00:26:12,080
Yes.

401
00:26:14,280 --> 00:26:16,840
You don't seem to be friends
with Chalard.

402
00:26:17,040 --> 00:26:19,400
It has nothing to do
with your investigation.

403
00:26:19,560 --> 00:26:21,200
Well, you know...

404
00:26:21,400 --> 00:26:24,760
Territorial lords can cross paths.

405
00:26:24,920 --> 00:26:26,920
Just like your property
is penetrable.

406
00:26:27,120 --> 00:26:30,360
Because it seems your guard
heard the dog barking last night.

407
00:26:30,560 --> 00:26:33,880
So, I'm going to check amongst
the bears if there's an intruder.

408
00:26:34,040 --> 00:26:36,360
If something happens to you,
it could come down on me.

409
00:26:36,520 --> 00:26:37,560
I can defend myself.

410
00:26:37,760 --> 00:26:39,720
-I don't need anyone.
-Ah, no?

411
00:26:40,080 --> 00:26:41,960
Unless you have a search warrant?

412
00:26:42,120 --> 00:26:43,760
Yes, I always have one on me.

413
00:26:43,960 --> 00:26:45,680
Little bear!
Hello!

414
00:26:45,880 --> 00:26:47,880
No, I think I left it at home.

415
00:26:48,400 --> 00:26:50,360
Come back when you've found it.

416
00:26:50,520 --> 00:26:53,000
OK. What time is it?

417
00:26:55,760 --> 00:26:57,840
Hello! Auntie Marteau is here.

418
00:26:58,440 --> 00:27:00,120
-9:58
-58?

419
00:27:00,320 --> 00:27:03,920
Show me. They're precise,
these pocket watches.

420
00:27:04,080 --> 00:27:05,360
My grandma had one.

421
00:27:05,560 --> 00:27:09,080
We must have put it on the...
well, we don't care.

422
00:27:09,240 --> 00:27:10,640
How much is the entry fee?

423
00:27:10,800 --> 00:27:12,520
Five euros. It's on the sign.

424
00:27:12,720 --> 00:27:16,120
Ah, really? I'm not sure if I have
that much on me. It's a lot.

425
00:27:16,280 --> 00:27:17,920
Do you do discounts

426
00:27:18,080 --> 00:27:20,680
for public servants,
part-time workers, etc.?

427
00:27:20,840 --> 00:27:22,200
Because it might be hard.

428
00:27:22,400 --> 00:27:25,840
Hey! What wouldn't we do
to come and see the beautiful bear?

429
00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:27,600
Come on, come on.

430
00:27:27,760 --> 00:27:28,760
OK, I'm off.

431
00:27:29,520 --> 00:27:30,640
See you soon!

432
00:27:38,800 --> 00:27:40,160
Hey! Mr. Chalard!

433
00:27:40,360 --> 00:27:43,320
There are bears. We're off to see
the wolves. Are you coming?

434
00:27:43,480 --> 00:27:45,000
OK, why not?

435
00:27:45,160 --> 00:27:47,000
"Wooo" says the wolf!

436
00:27:48,240 --> 00:27:50,360
So, if I understood,

437
00:27:50,560 --> 00:27:53,360
it seems like you have a problem
with Ms. Dewaere?

438
00:27:53,560 --> 00:27:56,200
The golf course? Yes,
it's not going well.

439
00:27:56,360 --> 00:27:58,120
It's hardcore country mentality.

440
00:27:58,560 --> 00:28:00,720
And Jeanne Dewaere
isn't very accommodating.

441
00:28:00,920 --> 00:28:03,920
I noticed. What does she have to do
with the golf course?

442
00:28:04,080 --> 00:28:05,800
Look at this house.

443
00:28:07,240 --> 00:28:09,360
Ideal for a panoramic restaurant.

444
00:28:10,440 --> 00:28:13,320
We could make the terrace bigger
and seat 80 people.

445
00:28:13,520 --> 00:28:16,520
Yeah! I have an idea:
upstairs rooms for the golfers,

446
00:28:16,720 --> 00:28:18,720
they can do 18 holes
and then after...

447
00:28:18,920 --> 00:28:20,840
-You see what I mean?
-Ah, yes.

448
00:28:21,040 --> 00:28:24,280
But, where does Jeanne put her tent?
Amongst the wolves?

449
00:28:24,480 --> 00:28:26,920
I'll make her a loft room
in the attic.

450
00:28:27,080 --> 00:28:28,760
She lives alone, you know?

451
00:28:28,960 --> 00:28:31,480
-Think of the lost space.
-I am!

452
00:28:31,680 --> 00:28:33,040
-She said no?
-Exactly.

453
00:28:33,200 --> 00:28:35,800
-She's the type to say no.
-I respect her.

454
00:28:36,000 --> 00:28:39,120
-But she has a character...
-Yes, how could we say it?

455
00:28:39,280 --> 00:28:42,600
She's difficult.

456
00:28:43,240 --> 00:28:45,560
Poor people don't know
what's good for them.

457
00:28:45,760 --> 00:28:48,520
Luckily, there are people like you
to do the thinking.

458
00:28:52,240 --> 00:28:53,680
-Captain!
-What?

459
00:28:54,200 --> 00:28:55,800
Sorry, Mr. Chalard, I must go.

460
00:28:55,920 --> 00:28:58,400
Don't hesitate to get in touch.

461
00:28:58,560 --> 00:29:00,200
I feel guilty for the guard.

462
00:29:00,400 --> 00:29:02,600
Guilty? How guilty?

463
00:29:02,840 --> 00:29:03,800
You killed him?

464
00:29:04,640 --> 00:29:06,960
I'm joking, Mr. Chalard!

465
00:29:07,400 --> 00:29:09,400
-So?
-The butt is at the lab,

466
00:29:09,600 --> 00:29:12,440
the cartridge, too.
For the piece of material,

467
00:29:12,640 --> 00:29:16,160
forensics was right--
it's from Zorro's cape.

468
00:29:17,000 --> 00:29:20,880
Otherwise, the guard,
Robert Perdriel, lived alone.

469
00:29:21,040 --> 00:29:21,840
He didn't want

470
00:29:22,040 --> 00:29:24,840
a weapon. He said that if he had one,
he wouldn't use it.

471
00:29:25,040 --> 00:29:26,080
-Not wrong.
-That's it.

472
00:29:26,240 --> 00:29:28,520
And the cartridge, for the moment,

473
00:29:28,720 --> 00:29:31,240
has nothing to do with our case,
but maybe...

474
00:29:31,440 --> 00:29:34,360
-well, we don't know.
-I don't understand what you said.

475
00:29:34,560 --> 00:29:37,800
I'm going for a run, to clear
my head, because you...

476
00:29:38,840 --> 00:29:40,280
I wasn't clear there...

477
00:29:49,200 --> 00:29:51,360
Yeah, yeah, keep going!
You can do it!

478
00:29:51,520 --> 00:29:55,240
Yeah! Yeah!

479
00:30:01,600 --> 00:30:02,720
Oh, hello!

480
00:30:03,120 --> 00:30:06,520
Look, I'm a redhead, too.
Look. I'm a ginger.

481
00:30:07,040 --> 00:30:08,280
Give me a kiss.

482
00:30:08,920 --> 00:30:10,840
You don't want to give me a kiss?

483
00:30:11,000 --> 00:30:12,600
OK, I'm off, then.

484
00:30:24,760 --> 00:30:26,640
Hello, Michel! It's nice to see you.

485
00:30:27,120 --> 00:30:28,800
-How are you, Gabriel?
-Good.

486
00:30:29,240 --> 00:30:31,800
A bit shaken, like everyone.

487
00:30:31,960 --> 00:30:34,560
-It must be hard for you.
-You can say that again.

488
00:30:34,760 --> 00:30:36,560
It's bad timing, with the elections.

489
00:30:36,760 --> 00:30:38,760
Yeah. It's not a good memory.

490
00:30:39,240 --> 00:30:41,600
What was the old guard's name?

491
00:30:41,760 --> 00:30:42,960
Arthur Lerois.

492
00:30:43,560 --> 00:30:45,160
He died in the same place.

493
00:30:45,360 --> 00:30:47,800
Except that it was
a real murder.

494
00:30:48,320 --> 00:30:49,680
He would have been 45.

495
00:30:50,680 --> 00:30:51,960
It's strange to grow old.

496
00:30:52,400 --> 00:30:55,440
While the dead, they stay
forever young.

497
00:30:56,080 --> 00:30:57,600
Do you know anything?

498
00:30:58,280 --> 00:31:01,880
As I always say, the best-informed
man in Entzheim is Gabriel.

499
00:31:02,080 --> 00:31:03,960
You know me. I don't like confusion.

500
00:31:04,960 --> 00:31:06,680
But I don't know if I should say

501
00:31:07,040 --> 00:31:09,080
that I found a strange mess
in the boss's trash.

502
00:31:09,240 --> 00:31:10,480
That's interesting.

503
00:31:11,200 --> 00:31:14,240
And that's not counting
the dog barking at 3:30 a.m.

504
00:31:15,240 --> 00:31:15,960
Here.

505
00:31:17,320 --> 00:31:18,280
I found this.

506
00:31:29,120 --> 00:31:30,480
Hello, little dogs.

507
00:31:34,760 --> 00:31:35,880
Brière.

508
00:31:36,400 --> 00:31:38,880
No, she's not far. Yes.

509
00:31:39,040 --> 00:31:40,640
Ah, yes, OK. Great.

510
00:31:40,840 --> 00:31:43,480
Thanks a lot. OK, I'll go right away.

511
00:32:05,640 --> 00:32:08,160
It isn't like the boss
to have a pink telephone.

512
00:32:08,840 --> 00:32:12,800
And you saw that it's not possible
to intrude into the park.

513
00:32:13,840 --> 00:32:15,720
Virgile reacts immediately.

514
00:32:15,920 --> 00:32:17,720
-Even from afar.
-Yeah?

515
00:32:17,880 --> 00:32:20,200
Well, apparently he was barking.

516
00:32:20,360 --> 00:32:22,440
Virgile? No, definitely not.

517
00:32:22,640 --> 00:32:25,560
-I would have heard him.
-Ah, OK.

518
00:32:25,760 --> 00:32:28,000
How do you like Ms. Dewaere ?

519
00:32:28,200 --> 00:32:29,960
A bit? A lot? Like crazy?

520
00:32:30,120 --> 00:32:31,160
I owe her everything.

521
00:32:31,800 --> 00:32:32,600
Do you know many

522
00:32:32,800 --> 00:32:35,200
women who hire ex-inmates
with no questions?

523
00:32:35,520 --> 00:32:37,480
Not really. It's not typical.

524
00:32:37,680 --> 00:32:39,920
That rhymes with trustworthy.

525
00:32:40,120 --> 00:32:43,280
Trustworthy to the point of lying
to cops, for example.

526
00:32:43,480 --> 00:32:45,680
Are there many ex-inmates ready
to do that?

527
00:32:46,040 --> 00:32:46,800
To cover her?

528
00:32:47,280 --> 00:32:49,680
Yeah, she helps anyone she can.

529
00:32:50,520 --> 00:32:51,600
I'll say something:

530
00:32:51,800 --> 00:32:53,600
when she took over the animal park,

531
00:32:54,720 --> 00:32:56,240
Arthur Lerois, the guard,

532
00:32:56,400 --> 00:32:58,440
he'd done six months for bodily harm.

533
00:32:58,920 --> 00:33:00,560
Everyone advised her to fire him.

534
00:33:01,920 --> 00:33:02,920
Interesting.

535
00:33:05,440 --> 00:33:06,560
Captain.

536
00:33:06,760 --> 00:33:09,760
We identified the victim.
It's Léonard Vincenne.

537
00:33:09,960 --> 00:33:12,600
A student on vacation
with his friend Julien Redon.

538
00:33:12,800 --> 00:33:14,560
The address is St.-George-les-Mines.

539
00:33:14,720 --> 00:33:16,240
OK. And the cartridge?

540
00:33:16,400 --> 00:33:18,440
It's from a Mauser 43.

541
00:33:20,120 --> 00:33:22,840
It was shot recently and look, here.

542
00:33:25,040 --> 00:33:26,920
A license for a Mauser.

543
00:33:27,200 --> 00:33:30,040
Jean-Marie Chalard.
Isn't that the father of...

544
00:33:30,600 --> 00:33:32,160
-of Michel?
-Yeah.

545
00:33:32,360 --> 00:33:34,080
-Where's my parka?
-Back there.

546
00:33:34,240 --> 00:33:36,320
Let's go and get it.

547
00:33:37,520 --> 00:33:38,640
Did you hear that?

548
00:33:39,640 --> 00:33:41,200
The Mauser was Chalard's.

549
00:33:41,360 --> 00:33:42,920
So, he killed the guard.

550
00:33:43,160 --> 00:33:46,000
I'm not surprised.
There's something about him.

551
00:33:47,000 --> 00:33:48,600
No, you're not right.

552
00:33:48,840 --> 00:33:50,560
Me and Chalard grew up together.

553
00:33:50,920 --> 00:33:52,280
He wouldn't touch a fly.

554
00:33:52,920 --> 00:33:54,440
You're naive, Gabriel.

555
00:33:54,600 --> 00:33:56,000
You always see the good.

556
00:33:56,160 --> 00:33:57,760
There's my parka.

557
00:33:57,960 --> 00:34:00,320
-Why did you forget it there?
-Sorry...

558
00:34:01,000 --> 00:34:04,280
Calm down. Look at it.
There's candy inside.

559
00:34:05,640 --> 00:34:06,840
OK, let's go.

560
00:34:07,040 --> 00:34:09,480
Go in front if it's dangerous.
There are wolves!

561
00:34:16,400 --> 00:34:18,040
Our last selfie with Léonard.

562
00:34:18,200 --> 00:34:19,680
Good reason to get rid of it.

563
00:34:21,120 --> 00:34:23,000
You don't realize.

564
00:34:24,200 --> 00:34:27,160
A firearm, a murder.
That's not what you told me.

565
00:34:27,920 --> 00:34:29,240
Ah, yes, the rifle shot.

566
00:34:30,080 --> 00:34:32,440
-I'd forgotten.
-How did you forget?

567
00:34:33,560 --> 00:34:36,720
Look at me. Answer me honestly.

568
00:34:37,160 --> 00:34:39,600
Do you know something
about the guard's death?

569
00:34:40,240 --> 00:34:42,520
Jeanne, I didn't even know
he was there!

570
00:34:43,320 --> 00:34:45,200
And Julien, he disappeared?

571
00:34:46,280 --> 00:34:47,960
I don't know. I have no news.

572
00:34:50,160 --> 00:34:51,240
Hold on.

573
00:34:51,880 --> 00:34:53,520
The police can't come to you.

574
00:34:53,680 --> 00:34:55,200
They can't prove anything.

575
00:34:56,120 --> 00:34:58,480
Now, you're going back to work.
Like normal.

576
00:34:59,120 --> 00:35:00,760
No, I can't, Jeanne!

577
00:35:00,920 --> 00:35:02,520
Of course you can!

578
00:35:04,680 --> 00:35:06,120
You're hard on me.

579
00:35:06,880 --> 00:35:08,280
Yeah, I'm hard.

580
00:35:09,360 --> 00:35:11,600
That's why I take risks
to save your skin!

581
00:35:11,760 --> 00:35:12,920
Little idiot!

582
00:35:14,120 --> 00:35:15,160
No, Jeanne, wait.

583
00:35:16,120 --> 00:35:17,000
Sorry.

584
00:35:18,880 --> 00:35:21,480
I didn't want to say that. I'm sorry.

585
00:35:30,480 --> 00:35:31,960
That's Julien Redon's house.

586
00:35:32,160 --> 00:35:34,440
-Are you sure?
-Yeah, pretty sure.

587
00:35:36,880 --> 00:35:39,640
What's going on?

588
00:35:39,840 --> 00:35:41,840
It's a police squad.

589
00:35:42,000 --> 00:35:44,080
Where do they think they are?

590
00:35:45,280 --> 00:35:47,520
Goddamn special forces.

591
00:35:48,000 --> 00:35:49,880
The crazier we get,
the more we laugh,

592
00:35:50,080 --> 00:35:52,720
-but not sure we have the same humor.
-No, that's true.

593
00:35:53,160 --> 00:35:56,720
Comrades. So, what's going on?

594
00:35:57,360 --> 00:35:59,880
Julien Redon has been
on the watchlist a while.

595
00:36:00,080 --> 00:36:03,520
The Interior Ministry saw
his texts online. Calls for uprising.

596
00:36:03,720 --> 00:36:05,800
So, we're taking over
the investigation.

597
00:36:06,360 --> 00:36:08,600
Procurer's orders.
It's come from the top.

598
00:36:08,760 --> 00:36:10,400
Well, if it's from the top...

599
00:36:10,800 --> 00:36:14,080
Is that Julien Redon ?

600
00:36:14,240 --> 00:36:15,200
Yes.

601
00:36:16,280 --> 00:36:17,920
He confessed to the murder.

602
00:36:18,640 --> 00:36:19,960
He said it was accidental.

603
00:36:20,160 --> 00:36:23,760
He says that he and Léonard
wanted to mock Michel Chalard.

604
00:36:23,960 --> 00:36:26,160
They wanted to attach
a banner to the trees.

605
00:36:26,320 --> 00:36:29,040
"To mock"? You police talk funny.

606
00:36:29,240 --> 00:36:30,760
Did Redon say there were three?

607
00:36:30,920 --> 00:36:33,520
No, there were just two.
Him and Vincenne.

608
00:36:34,880 --> 00:36:36,560
Sorry, Captain, we have work to do.

609
00:36:36,720 --> 00:36:38,560
Ah, yes, and we don't?

610
00:36:39,000 --> 00:36:40,960
This is ridiculous.

611
00:36:41,160 --> 00:36:44,040
If they're terrorists,
I'm the Dalai Lama.

612
00:36:44,760 --> 00:36:46,640
We're not going
to leave them, Captain?

613
00:36:46,840 --> 00:36:49,240
Let's keep going. We're on a roll.

614
00:36:49,440 --> 00:36:53,080
You just have to give them that.
It'll give them something to do.

615
00:36:53,480 --> 00:36:55,240
Are you joking? I found that.

616
00:36:55,800 --> 00:36:58,720
No, I won't.
We're not giving them that.

617
00:36:58,880 --> 00:37:01,920
Ah... concealment of proof...

618
00:37:02,280 --> 00:37:04,440
Do you want to enlist
in the Red Brigade?

619
00:37:04,600 --> 00:37:05,640
Anarchist!

620
00:37:05,800 --> 00:37:07,800
No, I'm joking. Look, did you see?

621
00:37:07,960 --> 00:37:09,240
When you left my parka,

622
00:37:09,440 --> 00:37:11,600
someone stole the phone.

623
00:37:12,560 --> 00:37:14,120
Nothing inside, no sim card.

624
00:37:14,280 --> 00:37:15,800
You're joking!

625
00:37:17,120 --> 00:37:19,840
I don't think I'm made
for this job. Dad was right.

626
00:37:20,000 --> 00:37:21,560
Your dad's a fool.

627
00:37:21,960 --> 00:37:23,520
Thanks to you, we're close.

628
00:37:23,720 --> 00:37:25,880
If we find who stole the sim card,

629
00:37:26,080 --> 00:37:28,680
we know who wants
to cover up the case.

630
00:37:28,880 --> 00:37:30,600
You understand? Here.

631
00:37:50,720 --> 00:37:51,720
What are you doing?

632
00:37:52,960 --> 00:37:53,840
Finally alone.

633
00:37:54,280 --> 00:37:56,240
I thought you'd appreciate
my discretion.

634
00:37:56,640 --> 00:37:59,240
Let me tell you,
you're in trouble, Jeanne.

635
00:38:00,760 --> 00:38:03,480
Impeding a terrorist
investigation case

636
00:38:03,880 --> 00:38:04,680
is bad.

637
00:38:04,920 --> 00:38:05,640
What?

638
00:38:06,480 --> 00:38:08,520
-Your protégée is at risk.
-Who?

639
00:38:08,720 --> 00:38:10,360
Manon. The little delinquent.

640
00:38:11,200 --> 00:38:12,400
It's maybe not my place,

641
00:38:12,600 --> 00:38:14,960
but you have a bad taste for thugs.

642
00:38:15,160 --> 00:38:17,440
Like Jean-Claude, the drug addict.

643
00:38:17,760 --> 00:38:19,680
-Ex.
-Ah, ex-drug addict.

644
00:38:20,000 --> 00:38:21,640
Or Arthur, the ex-guard.

645
00:38:21,840 --> 00:38:23,000
A real riffraff, that guy.

646
00:38:23,160 --> 00:38:24,640
Six months for bodily harm.

647
00:38:24,840 --> 00:38:28,120
Arthur was the most adorable
person I met.

648
00:38:29,680 --> 00:38:31,080
He was attacked.

649
00:38:32,000 --> 00:38:33,960
But the police didn't listen.

650
00:38:34,160 --> 00:38:36,600
In any case, this attraction
to criminals...

651
00:38:36,760 --> 00:38:38,480
Have you thought of psychoanalysis?

652
00:38:39,240 --> 00:38:40,200
What do you want?

653
00:38:40,680 --> 00:38:42,080
Still the same thing.

654
00:38:44,480 --> 00:38:46,280
Our agreement for the golf course.

655
00:38:50,240 --> 00:38:51,120
Get out of here.

656
00:38:52,440 --> 00:38:54,640
I know you're doing it to win votes.

657
00:38:55,000 --> 00:38:57,480
I have proof that Manon was involved,

658
00:38:57,840 --> 00:39:01,520
and that you've hidden the suspect
of a double terrorist act.

659
00:39:02,760 --> 00:39:05,240
I'm nice. I've said nothing...
until now.

660
00:39:10,080 --> 00:39:12,640
Look. My new project.

661
00:39:12,800 --> 00:39:14,080
It's a win-win situation.

662
00:39:14,720 --> 00:39:16,000
Congratulations.

663
00:39:16,280 --> 00:39:18,280
I'm convinced now not to sign.

664
00:39:20,000 --> 00:39:22,000
It's not a proposition,
it's blackmail.

665
00:39:22,480 --> 00:39:25,480
Ah... I understand.
You think I'm bluffing.

666
00:39:30,920 --> 00:39:32,800
-Hello?
-Captain Marleau?

667
00:39:33,000 --> 00:39:35,880
It's Michel Chalard. I just realized
I have a document

668
00:39:36,040 --> 00:39:37,600
that could help you.

669
00:39:38,120 --> 00:39:41,160
-Send it to Brière.
-No, I want to give it to you.

670
00:39:41,360 --> 00:39:43,240
-Where can we meet?
-My place, at 3:00 p.m.

671
00:39:43,400 --> 00:39:44,160
Perfect.

672
00:39:47,720 --> 00:39:49,600
You have until 3:00 p.m to sign.

673
00:39:54,440 --> 00:39:56,640
The judge has let us continue.

674
00:39:58,600 --> 00:40:01,120
You really want to look
for the sim card?

675
00:40:01,280 --> 00:40:02,480
It's worth a shot.

676
00:40:02,920 --> 00:40:04,960
Because, you see, Jeanne Dewaere

677
00:40:05,400 --> 00:40:08,240
was in a perfect position
to search through my parka.

678
00:40:08,640 --> 00:40:11,560
I don't like people going through
my things without asking.

679
00:40:12,640 --> 00:40:14,840
-So, what do we do?
-What do we do...

680
00:40:15,360 --> 00:40:18,040
Let's look through her file...
her judicial file.

681
00:40:18,240 --> 00:40:22,120
Because going through a cop's things
is the work of a pro.

682
00:40:22,320 --> 00:40:25,240
An innocent person wouldn't do that.

683
00:40:25,600 --> 00:40:29,560
It's clear, Jeanne Dewaere sent
the little Zorros there.

684
00:40:30,320 --> 00:40:33,080
Do you understand me?

685
00:40:46,200 --> 00:40:47,800
I was afraid you'd be closed.

686
00:40:48,040 --> 00:40:49,800
I would like some prickly flowers.

687
00:40:50,000 --> 00:40:52,000
Flowers like whips.

688
00:40:53,600 --> 00:40:56,120
-Are you seeing him?
-Yes.

689
00:40:59,680 --> 00:41:01,360
I don't know how you do it.

690
00:41:02,640 --> 00:41:04,080
With his boorish charm,

691
00:41:04,240 --> 00:41:05,760
he's so sexy!

692
00:41:08,000 --> 00:41:09,400
ENTZHEIM TOWN HALL

693
00:41:09,600 --> 00:41:10,800
So?

694
00:41:11,160 --> 00:41:13,520
I'm gonna break that Chalard's jaw

695
00:41:13,720 --> 00:41:15,120
and then denounce him.

696
00:41:15,320 --> 00:41:16,800
-And Manon?
-And you?

697
00:41:18,760 --> 00:41:20,320
Do you realize what you did?

698
00:41:20,840 --> 00:41:22,520
I helped a girl in need.

699
00:41:22,720 --> 00:41:25,360
And you stole from a cop.
Do you know the consequences?

700
00:41:25,720 --> 00:41:27,920
For a girl who is exploiting you.

701
00:41:28,040 --> 00:41:30,120
Like for all of them who abuse you.

702
00:41:31,280 --> 00:41:32,800
You've never said that before.

703
00:41:33,040 --> 00:41:33,840
You think that?

704
00:41:34,240 --> 00:41:36,320
I think that Manon
should tell the police.

705
00:41:36,520 --> 00:41:38,400
It wouldn't hurt her
to tell the truth.

706
00:41:38,840 --> 00:41:41,200
-And you stay out of it.
-It's a big risk.

707
00:41:41,360 --> 00:41:43,120
She needs to take responsibility.

708
00:41:43,320 --> 00:41:44,920
It was her own fault.

709
00:41:45,080 --> 00:41:46,640
Her life will be finished!

710
00:41:47,000 --> 00:41:48,400
We're all confused at 20!

711
00:41:49,440 --> 00:41:51,520
She's an adult.
She must be responsible.

712
00:41:51,680 --> 00:41:52,680
Responsible?

713
00:41:52,880 --> 00:41:55,000
Do you realize what you're saying?

714
00:41:56,040 --> 00:41:58,200
Complicity to murder,
that's ten years.

715
00:41:58,560 --> 00:42:00,320
And you don't just lose freedom.

716
00:42:00,480 --> 00:42:02,000
It's your dignity too!

717
00:42:02,840 --> 00:42:04,560
Your joy for life.

718
00:42:04,720 --> 00:42:06,280
You always speak about that.

719
00:42:06,760 --> 00:42:08,360
And then there's the boredom.

720
00:42:08,520 --> 00:42:10,840
Boredom which gnaws away at you.

721
00:42:11,320 --> 00:42:13,360
That's what prison means.

722
00:42:13,720 --> 00:42:15,560
Can you imagine her inside?

723
00:42:15,960 --> 00:42:18,400
No. I can't.

724
00:42:19,120 --> 00:42:20,040
And you?

725
00:42:21,040 --> 00:42:22,840
Thanks to you, I know what to do.

726
00:42:42,400 --> 00:42:43,520
Patrick, it's Alain.

727
00:42:43,720 --> 00:42:46,480
I need some confidential info
on someone I know.

728
00:42:46,840 --> 00:42:48,120
Jeanne Dewaere.

729
00:42:54,000 --> 00:42:55,400
NO TO THE GOLF COURSE

730
00:43:22,840 --> 00:43:23,520
Yeah.

731
00:43:25,240 --> 00:43:28,000
Are you sure it's not
another Jeanne Dewaere?

732
00:43:30,800 --> 00:43:31,720
Are you sure?

733
00:43:33,760 --> 00:43:35,120
Goddamnit!

734
00:43:47,520 --> 00:43:48,960
Mr. Chalard!

735
00:43:50,880 --> 00:43:52,240
It's me, it's Véronique.

736
00:43:54,240 --> 00:43:55,360
Mr. Chalard?

737
00:44:02,080 --> 00:44:03,440
Mr. Chalard?

738
00:44:20,600 --> 00:44:23,000
I can't believe it.
Léonard was really nice.

739
00:44:23,200 --> 00:44:25,560
Always a nice thing to say, helpful,

740
00:44:25,760 --> 00:44:28,840
all of them, Julien, Raoul, Frédéric.

741
00:44:29,040 --> 00:44:32,000
And the little florist. Manon.

742
00:44:32,200 --> 00:44:34,280
They love having a laugh, a drink.

743
00:44:34,720 --> 00:44:36,960
They did well in their village
with the shop.

744
00:44:37,160 --> 00:44:38,840
-There's things happening.
-Yeah.

745
00:44:39,040 --> 00:44:41,120
Dangerous terrorists, what a joke.

746
00:44:41,320 --> 00:44:43,920
It creates links. Shops are good.

747
00:44:44,080 --> 00:44:46,280
Do you know Jeanne Dewaere?

748
00:44:47,160 --> 00:44:48,840
Reserved, discrete, but nice.

749
00:44:49,040 --> 00:44:51,000
She looks after troubled kids.

750
00:44:51,200 --> 00:44:54,000
She finds them work, a place to stay.

751
00:44:54,240 --> 00:44:57,280
Ah, I know the story.
Ms. I-know-how-to-do-things-best.

752
00:44:57,480 --> 00:44:59,840
OK, I'll prepare you a nice lunch.

753
00:45:00,040 --> 00:45:01,800
It will rejuvenate you.

754
00:45:02,000 --> 00:45:03,720
-Thank you!
-Captain!

755
00:45:04,160 --> 00:45:04,960
Oh, yeah?

756
00:45:05,600 --> 00:45:06,440
You were right.

757
00:45:06,600 --> 00:45:08,720
I know, I'm always right.
It's my job.

758
00:45:08,880 --> 00:45:10,560
Jeanne Dewaere, formerly Ferrari,

759
00:45:10,760 --> 00:45:14,000
married Marco Ferrari
20 years ago, a real scoundrel.

760
00:45:14,200 --> 00:45:16,280
She was busted robbing a post office.

761
00:45:16,760 --> 00:45:19,280
One cop died, Marco, too.
Sentenced to 12 years,

762
00:45:19,480 --> 00:45:21,640
released after eight.
Look.

763
00:45:22,000 --> 00:45:23,920
Trial...
Ah, yes, Dewaere,

764
00:45:24,040 --> 00:45:25,360
that's why we missed it.

765
00:45:25,520 --> 00:45:27,440
"Robbery reaches its end."

766
00:45:27,640 --> 00:45:30,680
Well done! Let me buy you lunch.

767
00:45:43,320 --> 00:45:45,120
He's completely crazy.

768
00:45:50,440 --> 00:45:52,160
You know where your gloves were?

769
00:45:52,640 --> 00:45:53,880
In the greenhouse!

770
00:45:54,520 --> 00:45:57,080
Even a few seeds
can stuff everything up!

771
00:45:57,440 --> 00:45:58,720
What do I tell the lab?

772
00:45:59,160 --> 00:46:01,680
Due to someone who can't read,
we kill the wolves?

773
00:46:02,120 --> 00:46:03,520
Do you realize?

774
00:46:05,440 --> 00:46:06,160
You again.

775
00:46:06,760 --> 00:46:08,600
You're beautiful angry.

776
00:46:08,880 --> 00:46:10,000
But less than in photos.

777
00:46:13,720 --> 00:46:14,800
Let's go.

778
00:46:15,600 --> 00:46:16,840
After you, dear friend.

779
00:46:18,080 --> 00:46:18,680
Sir.

780
00:46:23,720 --> 00:46:26,400
What are you hoping for?
A signed confession?

781
00:46:27,040 --> 00:46:29,440
"I, Jeanne Dewaere,
am guilty of a murder."

782
00:46:29,640 --> 00:46:31,360
That would do nicely.

783
00:46:31,800 --> 00:46:33,160
You're such a cop.

784
00:46:33,320 --> 00:46:34,840
You don't want people to live.

785
00:46:35,560 --> 00:46:38,080
